# PR Review (Greptile Style)

When the user asks for a review, perform a structured multi-pass review of the current git diff. Run `git diff HEAD` (or `git diff main...HEAD` for branch comparisons) to get the changes, then analyze them across the categories below. Be concise, direct, and specific — cite file names and line numbers. Group findings by severity.

## Review Passes

### 1. Correctness & Bugs
- Logic errors, off-by-one, null/undefined dereferences
- Unhandled promise rejections or missing `await`
- Wrong HTTP methods, incorrect status codes
- Race conditions or missing error boundaries

### 2. Security
- Auth/authz gaps — are protected routes/actions actually gated?
- Secrets or credentials in code
- Unvalidated user input passed to DB queries, shell commands, or HTML
- Missing CSRF protection on mutations

### 3. Performance
- N+1 queries or missing pagination
- Large payloads sent to the client unnecessarily
- Missing `useMemo`/`useCallback` on expensive renders (React)
- Unnecessary re-renders or missing keys in lists

### 4. Type Safety (TypeScript)
- `any` used where a real type should exist
- Non-null assertions (`!`) without justification
- Missing return types on exported functions
- Types that lie (e.g., claiming something is non-optional when it can be `undefined`)

### 5. Code Quality
- Dead code or unused imports/variables
- Functions doing too many things — flag if >30 lines and not obvious why
- Duplicated logic that should be extracted
- Magic strings/numbers without constants

### 6. Tests & Observability
- New logic without test coverage
- Missing error logs on catch blocks that swallow errors
- Side effects (DB writes, emails, payments) not logged or traced

## Output Format

```
## Summary
<1–3 sentence overview of what the diff does>

## 🔴 Critical
- [file:line] <issue and suggested fix>

## 🟡 Important
- [file:line] <issue and suggested fix>

## 🟢 Suggestions
- [file:line] <non-blocking improvement>

## ✅ Looks Good
- <things done well — be genuine, not filler>
```

Use `🔴 Critical` for bugs, security issues, or data-loss risks. Use `🟡 Important` for correctness and type issues. Use `🟢 Suggestions` for style, performance hints, and nice-to-haves. Skip sections that have no findings. If the diff is clean, say so plainly.
